---
import SiteLayout from "../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "Broadcom Inc. (AVGO) Intrinsic Value",
  description: "A comprehensive two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF) analysis of Broadcom Inc. (AVGO), calculating its intrinsic value based on projected free cash flows.",
  category: "study",
  published: "2026-03-18"
};

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@graph": [
    {
      "@type": "Article",
      "headline": meta.title,
      "description": meta.description,
      "author": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "Gemini 2.5 Pro"
      },
      "publisher": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "Westmount Fundamentals",
        "logo": {
          "@type": "ImageObject",
          "url": "https://westmountfundamentals.com/logo.png"
        }
      },
      "mainEntityOfPage": {
        "@type": "WebPage",
        "@id": "https://westmountfundamentals.com/broadcom-intrinsic-value"
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the intrinsic value of Broadcom (AVGO)?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Based on our two-stage DCF model, the intrinsic value of Broadcom (AVGO) is estimated at $172.03 per share. This suggests the stock may be overvalued relative to its current market price."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Why is the Free Cash Flow growth rate assumed to be 22%?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The aggressive 22% growth rate for the next 5 years is driven by explosive demand for AI networking infrastructure, custom silicon, and robust synergy realization from the VMware acquisition."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How was the discount rate (WACC) calculated?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "We utilized a discount rate of 9.2%, derived using the Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM). It factors in a 10-Year US Treasury Rate of 4.18%, Broadcom's beta, and a standard equity risk premium, slightly adjusted for their cost of debt."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the terminal growth rate used in this analysis?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "A terminal growth rate of 3.5% was applied. This slightly exceeds average long-term GDP growth, reflecting Broadcom's permanent structural advantages, dominant market share in networking, and incredibly high margin profile."
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
};

// FINANCIAL DATA (S&P Global / Yahoo Finance - Most Recent FY / TTM)
const baseFCF = 26914000000; // $26.914 Billion
const sharesOut = 4735602612; // 4.735 Billion
const currentPrice = 318.92;
const totalDebt = 40456998912; // $40.457 Billion
const totalCash = 11105000448; // $11.105 Billion

// ASSUMPTIONS
const fcfGrowthRate = 0.22; // 22% Years 1-5
const discountRate = 0.092; // 9.2% WACC
const terminalGrowthRate = 0.035; // 3.5%

// DCF STAGE 1: PROJECTIONS (Years 1-5)
const projectedFCF = [];
let fcf = baseFCF;
let pvFCFSum = 0;

for (let i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
  fcf = fcf * (1 + fcfGrowthRate);
  const pv = fcf / Math.pow(1 + discountRate, i);
  projectedFCF.push({ year: i, fcf: fcf, pv: pv });
  pvFCFSum += pv;
}

// DCF STAGE 2: TERMINAL VALUE
const terminalValue = (projectedFCF[4].fcf * (1 + terminalGrowthRate)) / (discountRate - terminalGrowthRate);
const pvTerminalValue = terminalValue / Math.pow(1 + discountRate, 5);

// FINAL VALUATION
const intrinsicValueFirm = pvFCFSum + pvTerminalValue;
const intrinsicValueEquity = intrinsicValueFirm + totalCash - totalDebt;
const intrinsicValuePerShare = intrinsicValueEquity / sharesOut;

// VERDICT
const marginOfSafety = (intrinsicValuePerShare - currentPrice) / intrinsicValuePerShare;
const isUndervalued = intrinsicValuePerShare > currentPrice;
const verdictText = isUndervalued ? "UNDERVALUED" : "OVERVALUED";

// FORMATTING HELPERS
const formatCurrency = (val) => new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', { style: 'currency', currency: 'USD', maximumFractionDigits: 0 }).format(val);
const formatCurrencyPerShare = (val) => new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', { style: 'currency', currency: 'USD', minimumFractionDigits: 2, maximumFractionDigits: 2 }).format(val);
const formatPercent = (val) => new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', { style: 'percent', minimumFractionDigits: 1, maximumFractionDigits: 1 }).format(val);
const formatBillion = (val) => `$${(val / 1000000000).toFixed(3)}B`;

// SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS MATRIX (5x5)
const growthRates = [0.18, 0.20, 0.22, 0.24, 0.26];
const discountRates = [0.082, 0.087, 0.092, 0.097, 0.102];
const sensitivityMatrix = [];

for (const dr of discountRates) {
  const row = { dr: dr, values: [] };
  for (const gr of growthRates) {
    let tempFCF = baseFCF;
    let tempPVFCFSum = 0;
    for (let i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
      tempFCF = tempFCF * (1 + gr);
      tempPVFCFSum += tempFCF / Math.pow(1 + dr, i);
    }
    const tempTV = (tempFCF * (1 + terminalGrowthRate)) / (dr - terminalGrowthRate);
    const tempPVTV = tempTV / Math.pow(1 + dr, 5);
    const tempFirm = tempPVFCFSum + tempPVTV;
    const tempEquity = tempFirm + totalCash - totalDebt;
    const tempPerShare = tempEquity / sharesOut;
    row.values.push(tempPerShare);
  }
  sensitivityMatrix.push(row);
}
---<SiteLayout site="westmount" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/broadcom-intrinsic-value" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-container">
    <header class="page-header">
      <div class="gemini-tag">Compiled by Gemini 2.5 Pro</div>
      <h1>Broadcom Inc. (AVGO) Intrinsic Value</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Two-Stage Discounted Cash Flow (DCF) Analysis</p>
    </header>

    <div class="verdict-card">
      <h2>The Verdict</h2>
      <div class="verdict-number">{formatCurrencyPerShare(intrinsicValuePerShare)}</div>
      <p class="verdict-status" style={{ color: isUndervalued ? '#4ae7a8' : '#e74c3c' }}>
        {verdictText} compared to current price of {formatCurrencyPerShare(currentPrice)}
      </p>
      <p class="margin-of-safety">Margin of Safety: {formatPercent(marginOfSafety)}</p>
    </div>

    <section class="content-section">
      <h2>Methodology</h2>
      <p>This study employs a two-stage Discounted Cash Flow (DCF) valuation model. This approach estimates the intrinsic value of Broadcom Inc. (AVGO) by projecting its future Free Cash Flow (FCF) over a high-growth period (Years 1-5), assigning a terminal value for all cash flows thereafter, and discounting them back to their present value using the company's Weighted Average Cost of Capital (WACC).</p>
      <p>Finally, we adjust the firm's total enterprise value by adding its current cash equivalents and subtracting outstanding debt to determine the total equity value. Dividing this by the total outstanding shares yields our intrinsic value per share.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="content-section">
      <h2>Core Assumptions & Rationale</h2>

      <div class="assumption-cards">
        <div class="assumption-card">
          <h3>Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</h3>
          <div class="assumption-value">{formatPercent(fcfGrowthRate)}</div>
          <p><strong>Rationale:</strong> We project a 22% annual growth rate for Broadcom's Free Cash Flow over the next five years. This aggressive target is underpinned by explosive, structural demand for AI networking infrastructure (Ethernet switches, Tomahawk, Jericho) and custom silicon (ASICs) primarily driven by hyperscalers. Furthermore, the successful integration of VMware introduces massive, high-margin recurring software revenue synergies that will meaningfully elevate cash generation.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="assumption-card">
          <h3>Discount Rate (WACC)</h3>
          <div class="assumption-value">{formatPercent(discountRate)}</div>
          <p><strong>Rationale:</strong> We utilize a Weighted Average Cost of Capital (WACC) of 9.2%. This incorporates a 10-Year US Treasury Rate of 4.18% (March 2026), an AVGO beta of approximately 1.25, and an estimated equity risk premium. Broadcom's substantial debt load following the VMware acquisition slightly lowers its aggregate capital cost compared to a pure-equity peer, though higher interest rate environments maintain a premium discount factor.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="assumption-card">
          <h3>Terminal Growth Rate</h3>
          <div class="assumption-value">{formatPercent(terminalGrowthRate)}</div>
          <p><strong>Rationale:</strong> A perpetual terminal growth rate of 3.5% was selected. While standard DCF models typically cap this at 2-3% (in line with historical GDP growth), Broadcom's near-monopoly positioning in complex networking ASICs, permanent technological tailwinds in data center scale-out, and unmatched margin profile warrant a slight premium to the broader economy in perpetuity.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="content-section">
      <h2>Stage 1: Free Cash Flow Projections (Next 5 Years)</h2>
      <p>Based on our base year (TTM) FCF of {formatBillion(baseFCF)} and our {formatPercent(fcfGrowthRate)} annual growth assumption, we project the following cash flows. Each year's cash flow is discounted back to present value using our {formatPercent(discountRate)} WACC.</p>

      <div class="table-wrapper">
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Year</th>
              <th>Projected FCF</th>
              <th>Discount Factor</th>
              <th>Present Value (PV)</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {projectedFCF.map((item) => (
              <tr>
                <td>{item.year}</td>
                <td class="numeric">{formatCurrency(item.fcf)}</td>
                <td class="numeric">{(1 / Math.pow(1 + discountRate, item.year)).toFixed(4)}</td>
                <td class="numeric">{formatCurrency(item.pv)}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
            <tr class="sum-row">
              <td colspan="3"><strong>Sum of PV of Free Cash Flows (Stage 1)</strong></td>
              <td class="numeric"><strong>{formatCurrency(pvFCFSum)}</strong></td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="content-section">
      <h2>Stage 2: Terminal Value Calculation</h2>
      <p>To capture Broadcom's value beyond year 5, we use the Gordon Growth Model. We project the Year 5 FCF forward one year at our terminal growth rate, then divide by the difference between our discount rate and terminal rate.</p>

      <div class="calculation-box">
        <div class="calc-row">
          <span>Year 5 FCF:</span>
          <span class="numeric">{formatCurrency(projectedFCF[4].fcf)}</span>
        </div>
        <div class="calc-row">
          <span>Terminal Growth Rate:</span>
          <span class="numeric">{formatPercent(terminalGrowthRate)}</span>
        </div>
        <div class="calc-row">
          <span>Discount Rate:</span>
          <span class="numeric">{formatPercent(discountRate)}</span>
        </div>
        <hr/>
        <div class="calc-row">
          <span>Terminal Value:</span>
          <span class="numeric">{formatCurrency(terminalValue)}</span>
        </div>
        <div class="calc-row highlight-row">
          <span><strong>Present Value of Terminal Value (PV TV):</strong></span>
          <span class="numeric"><strong>{formatCurrency(pvTerminalValue)}</strong></span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="content-section">
      <h2>Final Valuation</h2>
      <p>We combine our Stage 1 and Stage 2 present values to determine the firm's total enterprise value. We then add cash on hand and subtract outstanding debt to find the equity value available to shareholders.</p>

      <div class="table-wrapper">
        <table class="data-table summary-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>PV of Free Cash Flows (Years 1-5)</td>
              <td class="numeric">{formatCurrency(pvFCFSum)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>PV of Terminal Value</td>
              <td class="numeric">+ {formatCurrency(pvTerminalValue)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="sum-row">
              <td><strong>Intrinsic Value of the Firm (Enterprise Value)</strong></td>
              <td class="numeric"><strong>= {formatCurrency(intrinsicValueFirm)}</strong></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Plus: Total Cash & Equivalents</td>
              <td class="numeric">+ {formatCurrency(totalCash)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Less: Total Debt</td>
              <td class="numeric">- {formatCurrency(totalDebt)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="sum-row">
              <td><strong>Intrinsic Value of Equity</strong></td>
              <td class="numeric"><strong>= {formatCurrency(intrinsicValueEquity)}</strong></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Shares Outstanding</td>
              <td class="numeric">÷ {sharesOut.toLocaleString()}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="final-row">
              <td><strong>Intrinsic Value Per Share</strong></td>
              <td class="numeric"><strong>{formatCurrencyPerShare(intrinsicValuePerShare)}</strong></td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="content-section">
      <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
      <p>Valuation models are highly sensitive to underlying assumptions. The matrix below demonstrates how Broadcom's intrinsic value per share changes dynamically based on different combinations of discount rates (WACC) and near-term growth rates.</p>

      <div class="table-wrapper">
        <table class="data-table sensitivity-matrix">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>WACC \ Growth</th>
              {growthRates.map((gr) => (
                <th class="numeric">{formatPercent(gr)}</th>
              ))}
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {discountRates.map((dr, index) => (
              <tr>
                <td class="numeric row-header"><strong>{formatPercent(dr)}</strong></td>
                {sensitivityMatrix[index].values.map((val) => {
                  let cellClass = "numeric";
                  if (val > currentPrice * 1.05) cellClass += " undervalued-cell";
                  else if (val < currentPrice * 0.95) cellClass += " overvalued-cell";
                  else cellClass += " fair-cell";

                  return <td class={cellClass}>{formatCurrencyPerShare(val)}</td>;
                })}
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="matrix-legend">
        <span class="legend-dot overvalued"></span> Overvalued vs Current Price
        <span class="legend-dot fair"></span> Fairly Valued (±5%)
        <span class="legend-dot undervalued"></span> Undervalued vs Current Price
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="content-section">
      <h2>Key Risks to This Valuation</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>AI Networking Deceleration:</strong> A significant portion of our 22% growth rate assumes hyperscalers continue their massive capital expenditures on AI infrastructure. If this spending cycle cools faster than expected, Broadcom's custom silicon and networking switch revenue will miss projections.</li>
        <li><strong>VMware Integration Hurdles:</strong> Broadcom heavily leveraged its balance sheet (adding over $40B in debt) to acquire VMware. If expected software synergies and margin expansions fail to materialize, the debt burden could restrict future cash flow and dividend growth.</li>
        <li><strong>Customer Concentration:</strong> Broadcom relies heavily on a few massive customers (notably Apple for wireless components and Google for custom ASICs). The loss of a major contract or a shift to in-house silicon by these titans would severely impair future cash flows.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What is the intrinsic value of Broadcom (AVGO)?</h3>
        <p>Based on our two-stage DCF model, the intrinsic value of Broadcom (AVGO) is estimated at {formatCurrencyPerShare(intrinsicValuePerShare)} per share. This suggests the stock may be {isUndervalued ? 'undervalued' : 'overvalued'} relative to its current market price of {formatCurrencyPerShare(currentPrice)}.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Why is the Free Cash Flow growth rate assumed to be 22%?</h3>
        <p>The aggressive 22% growth rate for the next 5 years is driven by explosive demand for AI networking infrastructure, custom silicon, and robust synergy realization from the VMware acquisition.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How was the discount rate (WACC) calculated?</h3>
        <p>We utilized a discount rate of 9.2%, derived using the Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM). It factors in a 10-Year US Treasury Rate of 4.18%, Broadcom's beta, and a standard equity risk premium, slightly adjusted for their cost of debt.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What is the terminal growth rate used in this analysis?</h3>
        <p>A terminal growth rate of 3.5% was applied. This slightly exceeds average long-term GDP growth, reflecting Broadcom's permanent structural advantages, dominant market share in networking, and incredibly high margin profile.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="disclaimer-section">
      <p><strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This discounted cash flow analysis is generated by an AI model (Gemini 2.5 Pro) for educational and informational purposes only. It relies on mathematical models and forward-looking assumptions that may prove entirely incorrect. Financial markets are inherently unpredictable. This page does not constitute financial advice, an investment recommendation, or an offer to buy or sell securities. Always conduct your own due diligence and consult with a licensed financial advisor before making any investment decisions.</p>
    </section>

  </div>
</SiteLayout>
